Metabolite Set Enrichment Analysis (MSEA) for metabolomics community

Atsushi Fukushima1* and Kozo Nishida2**

1RIKEN Center for Sustainable Resource Science
2RIKEN Quantitative Biology Center

*afukushima@gmail.com
**knishida@riken.jp

Abstract

Instructions for the MSEAp package.

Package: MSEAp

1 Introduction

One of the ultimate goals in systems biology is to elucidate the genotype-phenotype relationship in cellular systems [1]. Integrated omics approaches have received particular attention. Most omics analyses monitor the levels of target molecules like transcripts and metabolites. In this context, enrichment analysis approaches can be combined with pathway analysis to evaluate whether a particular molecular group is significantly over-represented, for example Gene Set Enrichment Analysis (GSEA) [2-3]. In meteabolomics, one of promising approaches is Metabolite Set Enrichment Analysis (MSEA) [4]. MSEAp is an R package for performing MSEA using both plant and animal metabolic pathways and metabolite-sets. The package can import pre-defined pathways like KEGG and SMPDB and user-defined metabolite sets in gmt format. Their metabolite sets are integrated and used for MSEA calculation. Given a metabolite-set or pathway annotation of metabolites, significance of the over-representation of the metabolites within the pathways is determined by a Fishers exact test. The visualization is based on previously established, a web server MSEA in MetaboAnalyst [5]. The package also contains pre-defined and extracted AraCyc that are publicly available and our curated metabolite-sets from MeKO [6], Arabidopsis flavonoid pathways (Tokimatsu, Nishida et al., in preparation), and literatures in plant metabolomics (AtMetExpress, in preparation).

3 Getting started

The following is an example of MSEA. mset_SMPDB_format_KEGG is a metabolite-set that has the metabolites for each pathway from the SMPDB [7] database with the metabolite ID from the KEGG [8] database.

kusano has KEGG metabolite IDs for MESA.

res is the MSEA result and the plot function visualizes the top 20 over-represented pathways.

library(MSEAp)
## 
## Attaching package: 'MSEAp'
## The following object is masked from 'package:graphics':
## 
##     barplot
data(mset_SMPDB_format_KEGG)
data(kusano)
res <- msea(mset_SMPDB_format_KEGG, kusano)
plot(res)

4 Appetizer

4.1 Importing users defined metabolite-sets

You can import users defined metabolite-sets in *.gmt format using read.gmt() function:

file <- system.file("extdata", "sample_SMPDB.gmt", package = "MSEAp")
smp <- read.gmt(file)

4.2 Importing KGML file

The function kgml.import() can extract compound set from KGML file (*.xml) to list.

file <- system.file("extdata/map00260.xml", package="KEGGgraph")## KGML downloaded from KEGG ftp
## kgml.import(file)

4.3 Importing KEGG pathways

The function setup.KEGG.gmt.R() generates metabolite-sets using the KEGG REST API.

res <- setup.KEGG.gmt(listformat = TRUE)

4.4 Conversion of KEGGs tar.gz into metabolite-set

The function setupPathwayClass() performs convertion of KEGGs tar.gz files (e.g.hsa.tar.gz) to metabolite-set list.

## filepath <- "./hsa.tar.gz" ## *.tar.gz downloaded from KEGG
## res <- setupPathwayClass(filepath) ## convert to list

4.6 For plant scientists

You can perform MSEA using AraCyc pathways and our curated metabolite sets (flavonoid pathways and some litterature).

data(mset_AraCyc_format_KEGG)
data(mset_AtMetExpress_Stress_format_KEGG)
data(mset_AtMetExpress_Flavonoids_format_KNApSAcK)
mset <- c(
  mset_AraCyc_format_KEGG,
  mset_AtMetExpress_Stress_format_KEGG,
  mset_AtMetExpress_Flavonoids_format_KNApSAcK
  )
length(mset) ## 281 metabolite-sets

5 Visualization of MSEA results

To help interpreting MSEA result, we also implemented barplot, dotplot and netplot for visualization.

barplot plots pvalue as color and the number of metabolite queries contained in the metabolite group as the height of bar.

dotplot plots dots on the expected value of msea in each group, with pvalue as color (like barplot) and the number of metabolite queries contained in the metabolite group as the size of dot.

netplot receives the edge list written with write.network beforehand and plots the pvalue in the MSEA result as the node color on the network of the metabolite group.

The option shared.metabolite in write.network decides how to connect the metabolite group with the edge.

In the example below, if there are more than 20 metabolites common among groups, we connect these groups with edge.

data(mset_SMPDB_Metabolic_format_HMDB)
data(msea.example)
res <- msea(mset_SMPDB_Metabolic_format_HMDB, msea.example)

dotplot(res)  ## You may have to zoom this plot in RStudio and other R working environments

barplot(res)  ## You can see the same plot by plot()

write.network(mset_SMPDB_Metabolic_format_HMDB, shared.metabolite = 20)
netplot(res, "./mset_SMPDB_Metabolic_format_HMDB_edges_share20.csv")
